IE48B_Final_Report

Yusuf Sina Öztürk

10/01/2022

Summary

In this report, we handle with hourly solar power prediction data with different kind of temperature data. The task is a prediction task. We have to predict one day later with not knowing today’s data. Basically, we are going to predict 2 days ahead.

The way I follow to have a nice model to do my prediction is like that:

  • First I start with doing only simple linear reggression with adding seasonal terms such as month and name of the day variables.

  • And then, I also added the temperature data which is provided to us. With that data, we actually has a pretty good R-squared value (~0.905).

  • Now, I need to improve my model by using regression tree based approach (EBLR).

  • After getting regresssion tree with respect to residuals, the leaf node with the highest percentage and highest value in it is choosen. And by following some approach, we are able to represent that node in my linear regression model.

  • After doing 3 iteration of EBLR, I improved R-square value to (~0.925) and I stopped.

  • Last step was doing prediction, becuase we have limited time, I used lagged variables for temperature data (48 lag).

  • Calculate the WMAPE value which is 10.5%. For that good R-square value our error metric is kind of high but we can improve that by doing some corrections because while our model predicting it predict negative values which is impossible.

Method

Reading the data, manipulation, adding seasonality variables and visualization

data <- as.data.table(data)
data[,datetime:=ymd(date)+dhours(hour)]
data=data[order(datetime)] #to be sure that the data is ordered

visualize the target variable production

ggplot(data ,aes(x=datetime,y=production)) + geom_line()

Adding trend, month and name of the day variables

#adding trend variable
data[,trnd:=1:.N]

#adding name of the days and month variable
data[,w_day:=as.character(wday(datetime,label=T))]
data[,mon:=as.character(month(datetime,label=T))]

First Linear Regression Model

Now, we can create one linear regression model with using only seasonal terms.

## F-statistic:   912 on 216 and 20056 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

Our R-squared value increased a lot by adding these temperature variables in our model. However, we have to consider that when we add new temperature variables in the model some of the seasonal terms lose their importance in the model.

We are not going to eliminate those not needed variables from the model because of the limited time.

Let us check how our lm_base_two model behave compared to actual values by getting predicted values.

tmp=copy(data)
tmp[,actual:=production]
tmp[,predicted:=predict(lm_base_two,tmp)]

ggplot(tmp[date=='2020-09-01'] ,aes(x=datetime)) +
  geom_line(aes(y=actual,color='real')) + 
  geom_line(aes(y=predicted,color='predicted'))

Even this base model seems well fitted into our model.

EBLR Method

Now we can use EBLR approach to improve our model.

First, we need to get residuals to fit a tree.

tmp[,residual:=actual-predicted]

We have some problems with not using variables while creating a regression tree so I have to create another data table named tmp2. Sorry for that!

tmp2 <- tmp[,-c("date", "production","datetime","actual","predicted")]

So now we are able to get tree with using rpart function.

fit_res_tree=rpart(residual~.,tmp2,
                   control=rpart.control(cp=0,maxdepth=4))

Let me visualize our regression tree.

fancyRpartPlot(fit_res_tree)

So the most right tree leaf node has the biggest value and has 7% percentage. Therefore, we are going to use that leaf node in our first iteration.

Adding those variables to the dataset, to represent that leaf node.

tmp[,DSWRF_38_35_depth_1:=as.numeric(DSWRF_surface_38_35 < 190)]
tmp[,DSWRF_38_35_depth_2:=as.numeric(DSWRF_surface_38_35 >= 23)]
tmp[,DSWRF_39_35.25_depth_3:=as.numeric(DSWRF_surface_39_35.25 < 186)]
tmp[,month_depth_4:=as.numeric(!mon %in% c('Apr','Feb','Mar','Nov','Oct','Sep'))]

Now, we can create another linear regression model with that leaf node represented in it.

lm_base_two_iter1=lm(production~. - datetime - date - hour + as.factor(hour) -residual - predicted - actual - DSWRF_38_35_depth_1 - DSWRF_38_35_depth_2 - DSWRF_39_35.25_depth_3 -month_depth_4 
                     + DSWRF_38_35_depth_1:DSWRF_38_35_depth_2:DSWRF_39_35.25_depth_3:month_depth_4
                       ,tmp)

summary(lm_base_two_iter1)

ggplot(tmp[date=='2020-09-01'] ,aes(x=datetime)) +
  geom_line(aes(y=actual,color='real')) + 
  geom_line(aes(y=predicted,color='predicted'))

Now we can get new residuals.

tmp[,residual:=actual-predicted]

Again we have some problems with not using variables while creating a regression tree so I have to create another data table named tmp3

tmp3 <- tmp[,-c("date", "production","datetime","actual","predicted", "DSWRF_39_35.25_depth_3", "month_depth_4", "DSWRF_38_35_depth_1","DSWRF_38_35_depth_2")]

Now, I can get tree with using rpart function

fit_res_tree_iter2=rpart(residual~.,tmp3,
                   control=rpart.control(cp=0,maxdepth=4))

Let me visualize our regression tree.

fancyRpartPlot(fit_res_tree_iter2)

Again on the most right leaf node we have the biggest percentage and biggest value so we can do iteration for that part.

Adding those variables to the dataset, to represent that leaf node.

tmp[,iter_2_depth_1:=as.numeric(DSWRF_surface_39_36 >= 11)]
tmp[,iter_2_depth_2:=as.numeric(DSWRF_surface_38.5_36 < 139)]
tmp[,iter_2_depth_3:=as.numeric(!mon %in% c('Aug','Dec','Jan','Jul','Jun','Mar','May'))]
tmp[,iter_2_depth_4:=as.numeric(DSWRF_surface_39_35.25 < 184)]

Now, we can create another linear regression model with that leaf node represented in it.

lm_base_two_iter2=lm(production~. - datetime - date - hour + as.factor(hour) -residual - predicted - actual 
                     - DSWRF_38_35_depth_1 - DSWRF_38_35_depth_2 - DSWRF_39_35.25_depth_3 -month_depth_4 
                     - iter_2_depth_1 - iter_2_depth_2- iter_2_depth_3- iter_2_depth_4 
                     + DSWRF_38_35_depth_1:DSWRF_38_35_depth_2:DSWRF_39_35.25_depth_3:month_depth_4 
                     + iter_2_depth_1:iter_2_depth_2:iter_2_depth_3:iter_2_depth_4
                     ,tmp)

summary(lm_base_two_iter2)

Our R-squared value increased by 0.5% but we can do one more iteration.

Need to see how fitted our second iteration.

tmp[,predicted:=predict(lm_base_two_iter2,tmp)]

ggplot(tmp[date=='2020-09-01'] ,aes(x=datetime)) +
  geom_line(aes(y=actual,color='real')) + 
  geom_line(aes(y=predicted,color='predicted'))

Now we can get new residuals.

tmp[,residual:=actual-predicted]

Again we have some problems with not using variables while creating a regression tree so I have to create another data table named tmp4

tmp4 <- tmp[,-c("date", "production","datetime","actual","predicted", "DSWRF_39_35.25_depth_3", "month_depth_4", "DSWRF_38_35_depth_1","DSWRF_38_35_depth_2","iter_2_depth_1","iter_2_depth_2","iter_2_depth_3","iter_2_depth_4")]

Now, I can get tree with using rpart function

fit_res_tree_iter3=rpart(residual~.,tmp4,
                         control=rpart.control(cp=0,maxdepth=4))

fancyRpartPlot(fit_res_tree_iter3)

For this iteration i will going to get the leaf node with the biggest value which has 38% somewhere in the middle of the tree.

Adding those variables to the dataset, to represent that leaf node.

tmp[,iter_3_depth_1:=as.numeric(RH_2.m.above.ground_38.25_36 < 96)]
tmp[,iter_3_depth_2:=as.numeric(TMP_2.m.above.ground_38.25_35 >= 274)]
tmp[,iter_3_depth_3:=as.numeric(hour<17)]
tmp[,iter_3_depth_4:=as.numeric(TCDC_middle.cloud.layer_38.75_35.75 < 0.65)]

Now, we can create another linear regression model with that leaf node represented in it.

lm_base_two_iter3=lm(production~. - datetime - date - hour + as.factor(hour) -residual - predicted - actual 
                     - DSWRF_38_35_depth_1 - DSWRF_38_35_depth_2 - DSWRF_39_35.25_depth_3 -month_depth_4 
                     - iter_2_depth_1 - iter_2_depth_2- iter_2_depth_3- iter_2_depth_4 
                     - iter_3_depth_1 - iter_3_depth_2- iter_3_depth_3- iter_3_depth_4 
                     + DSWRF_38_35_depth_1:DSWRF_38_35_depth_2:DSWRF_39_35.25_depth_3:month_depth_4 
                     + iter_2_depth_1:iter_2_depth_2:iter_2_depth_3:iter_2_depth_4
                     + iter_3_depth_1:iter_3_depth_2:iter_3_depth_3:iter_3_depth_4
                     ,tmp)

So recall that in second iteration our R-squared value is 0.9209. In third iteration R-squared value is 0.9253. Therefore, I stop to do more iteration.

Prediction

Now time to do prediction.

To compare my prediction, I am going to predict the last 2 days production values to calculate WMAPE value.

Also because we have limited time to finish this task, I am going to take all the temperature data (naively) from 2 days ago directly.

testdata <- tmp[c(20233:20280),]

traindata <- copy(tmp)
traindata <- as.data.frame(traindata)
for (i in 1:48){
  for (j in 3: 197){
    traindata[(20232 + i), j] <- traindata[(20184 + i),j]
  }
}

So we have lagged variables in our train data. We can do prediction.

tmp[,predicted:=predict(lm_base_two_iter3,tmp)]
predicted_values <- tmp$predicted[20233:20280]

predicted_values[is.na(predicted_values)] = 0
for (i in 1:48){
  if(predicted_values[i] < 0){
    predicted_values[i] <- 0
  }
}

Now we can calculate our WMAPE value for our model.

WMAPE Calculation

Because our task is to predict one day later with knowing one day before data. While we are calcultaing WMAPE, we need to use only last 24 data of the actual and predicted values

numerator = 0
denom = 0

for ( i in 25:48){
  numerator = numerator + actual_values[i] - predicted_values[i]
  denom = denom + actual_values[i] 
}

WMAPE = numerator / denom
WMAPE
## [1] 0.1069358

So we have 10.6% error with using 3 iteration of ELBR approach.

Discussion

In order to improve our prediction:

  • We can do more iterations have better model.

  • We can also predict the temperature values. Not only getting the lagged values. Meteorology data can also help us about that.

  • While we are choosing the node from the regression tree, we can do more analysis. I basicaly choose the highest values and highest percentage one.
